{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}} {{Use British English|date=June 2013}} {{Infobox person |name = Ann Cargill |image = Ann cargill mw114486.jpg |alt = |caption = As "Duenna" of Sheridan |birth_name = Ann Brown |birth_date = 1760 |birth_place = |death_date = 4 {{Death year and age|1784|1760|3}} |death_place = [[Isles of Scilly]] |nationality = British |occupation = Opera singer }}
'''Ann Cargill''' (born Ann Brown) (1760 – 4 March 1784) was a British [[opera]] [[diva]] and celebrated beauty whose life and death were a sensation in [[London]] at the close of the 18th century.
==Death== [[File:Ann cargill.PNG|thumb|''Tempest'', Miss Brown and Mr. Mattocks in the characters of Miranda and Ferdinand]]
By 1783, she had a new love. Her lover was in the [[British East India Company]] and stationed in [[Calcutta]], so she left England for [[India]]. In 1783, she performed operatic parts in Calcutta, to tremendous applause, and her benefit night brought in "the astonishing sum of 12,000 rupees."<ref>(Baldwin and Wilson, 93)</ref><ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Cargill, Ann |first=John Joseph|last=Knight|volume=9}}</ref>
She was a passenger on the [[packet ship]] [[Nancy (1774 EIC ship)|''Nancy'']], whose captain, John Haldane, was her lover, when it wrecked and sank off the [[Isles of Scilly]] on 4 March 1784. Her body, originally unidentified, was buried on [[Rosevear]] then reburied at [[St Mary's Old Church, St Mary's|Old Town Church]] on [[St Mary's, Isles of Scilly|St Mary's]] in the [[Isles of Scilly]]. The newspaper accounts of her death and how the body had been found "floating in her shift" with an infant at her bosom made her a tragic figure for the English press. In September 2008, British divers claimed to have found the wreck of the ''Nancy'', further out from the Isles of Scilly than was previously thought.<ref>{{cite news | last = Morris | first = Steven | title = Wrecks: We have found rich opera singer's ship, say divers | work = [[The Guardian]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = 2008-09-18 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/sep/18/1 | accessdate = 2008-09-19 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = de Bruxelles | first = Simon | title = Divers close in on lost fortune of Ann Cargill, a scandalous star | work = [[The Times]] | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = 2008-09-18 | url = http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/the_way_we_live/article4775914.ece | accessdate = 2008-09-19 | location=London}}</ref>
==Further reading== *{{cite book | last = Stevens | first = Todd | authorlink = |author2=Cumming, Edward | title = Ghosts of Rosevear and the wreck of the Nancy Packet | publisher = | location = | pages = | url = http://www.ghostsofrosevear.co.uk | doi = | id = | isbn = }}
