'''Non-invasive cerebellar stimulation''' is the application of non-invasive [[neurostimulation]] techniques on the [[cerebellum]] to modify its electrical activity. Techniques such as [[transcranial magnetic stimulation]] (TMS) or [[transcranial direct current stimulation]] (tDCS) can be used<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grimaldi|first=G.|last2=Argyropoulos|first2=G. P.|last3=Boehringer|first3=A.|last4=Celnik|first4=P.|last5=Edwards|first5=M. J.|last6=Ferrucci|first6=R.|last7=Galea|first7=J. M.|last8=Groiss|first8=S. J.|last9=Hiraoka|first9=K.|date=February 2014|title=Non-invasive cerebellar stimulation--a consensus paper|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23943521|journal=Cerebellum (London, England)|volume=13|issue=1|pages=121–138|doi=10.1007/s12311-013-0514-7|issn=1473-4230|pmid=23943521}}</ref>. The cerebellum is a high potential target for neuromodulation of [[neurology|neurological]] and [[psychiatry|psychiatric]] disorders due to the high density of neurons in its superficial layer, its electrical properties, and its participation in numerous closed-loop circuits involved in [[motor function|motor]], [[cognitive function|cognitive]], and emotional functions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=van Dun|first=Kim|last2=Manto|first2=Mario|date=27 December 2017|title=Non-invasive Cerebellar Stimulation: Moving Towards Clinical Applications for Cerebellar and Extra-Cerebellar Disorders|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12311-017-0908-z|journal=The Cerebellum|language=en|volume=17|issue=3|pages=259–263|doi=10.1007/s12311-017-0908-z|issn=1473-4222}}</ref>
Cerebellar TMS is a relatively new field that is undergoing experimental research. There is yet no evidence of the therapeutic effects of it.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Minks|first=Eduard|last2=Kopickova|first2=Marie|last3=Marecek|first3=Radek|last4=Streitova|first4=Hana|last5=Bares|first5=Martin|date=June 2010|title=Transcranial magnetic stimulation of the cerebellum|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20668494|journal=Biomedical Papers of the Medical Faculty of the University Palacky, Olomouc, Czechoslovakia|volume=154|issue=2|pages=133–139|issn=1213-8118|pmid=20668494}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Deep brain stimulation]] *[[Transcranial alternating current stimulation]] (tACS) *[[Transcranial random noise stimulation]] (tRNS)
