'''Roy Charles Amara''' (7 April 1925<ref name=Congress>{{cite web |title= Amara, Roy |url= http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n77010151.html |publisher= Library of Congress |accessdate= 18 February 2015 |quote= data sheet (Amara, Roy Charles, b. 4/7/25) }}</ref> – 31 December 2007<ref name=Obit>{{cite news|last1=Pescovitz|first1=David|title=Roy Amara, forecaster, RIP|url=http://boingboing.net/2008/01/03/roy-amara-forecaster.html|accessdate=18 February 2015|work=BoingBoing|date=3 January 2008}}</ref>) was an [[United States|American]] researcher, scientist, [[Futures studies|futurist]]<ref>[http://www.neatorama.com/2012/09/05/Four-Geeky-Laws-That-Rule-Our-World/ Four Geeky Laws That Rule Our World]</ref> and president of the [[Institute for the Future]] best known for coining Amara's law on the effect of [[technology]]. He held a BS in Management, an MS in the Arts and Sciences, and a Ph.D. in Systems Engineering,<ref name=Arizona_Uni>{{cite web|title=Roy Amara (biography)|url=http://ag.arizona.edu/futures/fut/amara.html|publisher=University of Arizona: Anticipating the future (course), Futures Thinkers|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref> and also worked at the [[SRI International|Stanford Research Institute]].

== Amara's law ==
His [[adage]] about forecasting the effects of technology has become known as Amara's law and states:

<blockquote>''We tend to overestimate the effect of a technology in the short run and underestimate the effect in the long run.''<ref>{{cite book |title=Oxford Essential Quotations |editor=Susan Ratcliffe |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2016 |edition=4th |chapter=Roy Amara 1925–2007, American futurologist |chapter-url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780191826719.001.0001/q-oro-ed4-00018679 }}</ref><ref name=PC_Mag>{{cite journal|title=Encyclopedia: Definition of: Amara's law|journal=PC Magazine|url=https://www.pcmag.com/encyclopedia/term/37701/amara-s-law|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Doc Searls |title=The Intention Economy: When Customers Take Charge |publisher=Harvard Business Press |year=2012 |isbn=978-1-4221-5852-4 |page=257 }}</ref></blockquote>

This law has been described as encouraging people to think about the long-term effects of technology,<ref>[http://www.techradar.com/news/world-of-tech/10-laws-of-tech-the-rules-that-define-our-world-1067906 10 laws of tech: the rules that define our world]</ref> and has been described as best illustrated by the [[hype cycle]],<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180410135130/https://spotlessdata.com/blog/amaras-law Amara's Law]</ref> characterized by the "peak of inflated expectations" followed by the "trough of disillusionment".<ref>[http://www.neatorama.com/2012/09/05/Four-Geeky-Laws-That-Rule-Our-World/ Hyper Cycle for Emerging Technologies]</ref> The law has been used in explaining [[cyber-attack]]s<ref>[https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/vtech-breach-amaras-law-long-term-effects-cyber-attacks-sherif-koussa VTech Breach, Amara's Law and Long-term Effects of Cyber Attacks]</ref> and [[nanotechnology]].<ref>[https://www.researchgate.net/figure/271929362_fig1_FIGURE-1-Amara's-law-of-correlation-for-nanotechnology-showing-nanohazards-in-long-run Context]</ref>

